{"cursor":"6171","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{| align=right style=\"border:1px solid\" !style=\"background:#ccffcc;\"\ncolspan=3|'Sima Xiangru's [[Chinese name|names]]'\n|-\n| || Given name || Style name\n|- Traditional || å¸é¦¬ç¸å¦ || é·å¿ - Simplified || å¸é©¬ç¸å¦\n||| é¿å¿ - Pinyin || SÄ«mÇ XiÄngrÃº || ChÃ¡ngqÄ«ng - Wade-\n|Giles || Ssu1-ma3 Hsiang1-ju2 || Chang2-ch'ing1 }\n\n\n'Sima Xiangru' å¸é©¬ç¸å¦, also known as 'Ssu-ma Hsiang-ju' å¸é¦¬ç¸å¦ (179â127 BC) was a\nChinese poet, musician, and author of the Western Han Dynasty (206 BCE â 9 CE).\nSima's importance in Classical Chinese poetry consists both in his surviving\nworks, several of which are especially famous, but also in his contribution to\ninnovation in form and style. His poetry includes his invention or at least\ndevelopment of the [[fu (poetry)|fu]] form, Hawkes, 193 applying new\nmetrical rhythms to the lines of poetry, which he mixed with lines of prose, and\nprovided with several of what would in ensuing centuries become among a group of\ncommon set topics for this genre. He was also versatile enough to write in the\n[[Chu Ci|Chu Ci-style]], while it was enjoying a brief renaissance, and he also\nwrote lyrics in what would become known as the [[yuefu]] formal style.\nMusically, Sima Xiangru is known for mastery of the [[guqin]].\n\nSima Xiangru's life is a topic of biographical interest, and is featured in\nwhat enthusiasts like to refer to as the [[Records of the Grand Historian]],\nbut more prosaically is called the Shiji. Much is known about Sima Xiangru\nthrough Sima Qian's biography of him, in Shij ji 117. Sima Qian. \"Shi ji\n117: Biography of Sima Xiangru.\" Pp. 259-306 in Vol 2 of Records of the Grand\nHistorian. Han Dynasty. Burton Watson, trans. New York: Columbia University\nPress, 1993. Sima Xiangru not only lived the good life as a member of two\nroyal courts at different times of his life, but also experienced periods of\nfinancial and political difficulty: once he was disappointed in love, being\nforbidden marriage to the daughter of a wealthy man, but then eloped with his\nlover, in a famous scandal, where the couple supported themselves by opening\nand running a small tavern.\n","linknr":197,"url":"Sima_Xiangru","recorded":1375066211,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Sima_Xiangru&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Sima_Xiangru&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Chinese_name","/wiki/Chinese_name","/wiki/Chinese_style_name","/wiki/Traditional_Chinese","/wiki/Simplified_Chinese","/wiki/Pinyin","/wiki/Wade-Giles","/wiki/Chinese_name","/wiki/Chinese_surname","/wiki/Sima_(surname)","/wiki/Chinese_poet","/wiki/Western_Han_Dynasty","/wiki/Classical_Chinese_poetry","/wiki/Fu_(poetry)","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Chu_Ci","/wiki/Yuefu","/wiki/Guqin","/wiki/Records_of_the_Grand_Historian","/wiki/Sima_Qian","#cite_note-2","#Names","#Life","#Career","#Works","#Influence","#See_also","#Notes","#References","/w/index.php?title=Sima_Xiangru&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Lin_Xiangru","/wiki/State_of_Zhao","/w/index.php?title=Sima_Xiangru&action=edit&section=2","/wiki/File:Zhuo_Wenjun.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Zhuo_Wenjun